<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Panasonic in US kitchens means microwaves — that's the scope, and we're honest about it.</h2>

    <p>Panasonic's residential appliance footprint in the United States is narrower than most homeowners realize. The brand exited the US major-appliance market years ago — there are no Panasonic refrigerators, washers, dryers, dishwashers, wall ovens, or cooktops in the current US lineup, and there haven't been for some time. What Panasonic still sells, supports, and ships parts for in the US is the microwave family: NN-SN Inverter built-ins, NN-CS combo steam ovens, and Genius Prestige countertops. That's the scope we service.</p>

    <p>Within that scope, Panasonic is one of the more interesting brands on the truck. <strong>Inverter Technology</strong> — Panasonic's signature microwave architecture, where a continuous-power inverter board replaces the on/off duty cycling of conventional magnetron drive — was the brand's market disruption in the 2000s and is still the technical reason most chefs and dedicated home cooks specify Panasonic over the alternatives. Smooth simmer at 30% power on a Panasonic Inverter unit actually simmers; the same 30% setting on a conventional magnetron is just the magnetron firing for three seconds out of every ten. The trade-off, on the service side, is that Inverter boards add a failure mode that conventional Sharp or GE microwaves don't have.</p>

    <p>One observation worth keeping: Panasonic microwaves built between roughly 2010 and 2018 are often more reliable than the current generation. The Inverter boards from that era used heavier capacitors and beefier output stages; current production has thinned the bill of materials in places we see in repair patterns. If you have a 2014 NN-SN that's still going, keep it.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 NN-SN BUILT-IN -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, NN-SN Inverter built-ins</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">NN-SN series — the Panasonic built-in we see most.</h2>

    <p class="lead">The NN-SN series is the Inverter-equipped built-in line: NN-SN966S, NN-SN686S, NN-SD975S, NN-SD681S. These are the units installed into custom kitchen cabinetry behind a trim kit, almost always as a second microwave (next to the steam oven, in the butler's pantry, in a beverage center) rather than as a primary cooking microwave. Built-in installation is what makes service economics tilt strongly toward repair over replacement: a 36-inch trim-kit cutout fits one specific Panasonic unit, and replacing the appliance with a different brand means cabinet rework.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 6-8 magnetron failure:</strong> The NN-SN966S and NN-SN686S magnetrons cluster their failure window tightly around the 7-year mark in our LA service data. Symptom is the classic hum-without-heat — fan and turntable run, display normal, food stays cold. OEM Panasonic magnetron $180-$280 part, $245-$345 with labor. We keep the common NN-SN magnetron stocked on the truck.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-9 inverter board:</strong> Post-2018 NN-SN units have shown a higher inverter-board failure rate than the 2010-2018 generation. Diagnostic looks similar to magnetron failure (hum without heat) but bench-tests differently. Inverter board $185-$285 OEM, $260-$385 with labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8+ control board (E05):</strong> Less common but more consequential. E05 fault clears occasionally with a 10-minute breaker reset; persistent E05 means control board replacement at $245-$345, and on a 10-plus-year unit we usually have the repair-versus-replace conversation honestly before quoting the part.</li>
      <li><strong>Door switch (any age):</strong> Triple-interlock system, one switch fails and the unit refuses to start. $35-$65 part, 30-minute repair.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 NN-CS COMBO STEAM -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, NN-CS combo steam ovens</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">NN-CS894S and the steam-generator service tree.</h2>

    <p class="lead">The NN-CS combo steam ovens are Panasonic's premium countertop offering — $2,500-$3,500 retail, combining microwave, convection, steam, and grill in a single counter unit. We see the NN-CS894S regularly in Bel Air, Beverly Hills, Hollywood Hills, and Pacific Palisades estate kitchens, almost always as a second oven in a butler's pantry or breakfast-bar setting alongside a primary Wolf, Miele, or Thermador wall oven.</p>

    <p>Service tree on NN-CS combo units is more mechanical than electronic. The two recurring service items, in order of frequency:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Steam-generator scaling:</strong> LA's hard water — particularly in the Hills neighborhoods (Bel Air, Beverly Hills, Hollywood Hills) where well-fed and softener-fed water mixes — builds limescale inside the steam reservoir faster than Panasonic's recommended descaling cadence. Steam cycle goes weak, then the unit alarms a steam fault. Descale flush with citric solution restores normal steam performance for $145-$215.</li>
      <li><strong>Door seal at year 6+:</strong> The combo door's perimeter seal degrades with the steam-cycle thermal swings. When the seal opens up, oven-cavity heat retention drops and convection-bake performance falls visibly. Seal replacement is $185-$285 with labor, restores cavity-temperature stability.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Inverter and control electronics on NN-CS units are durable; we rarely replace boards on these.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 GENIUS PRESTIGE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Genius Prestige countertop</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Countertop Panasonic — Genius Prestige and Genius Sensor lines.</h2>

    <p class="lead">The Genius Prestige and earlier Genius Sensor countertop lines are Panasonic's mainstream consumer microwaves — accessible repair, more replaceable economics than the built-ins. Common service across the line:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Door-switch alignment:</strong> Pre-2015 Genius Prestige units developed a known door drift after several thousand cycles — the door physically settles and stops triggering one of the three interlock switches. Switch replacement plus alignment shim is $65-$110 with labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Turntable drive coupler:</strong> $15 OEM part, 10-minute change. Most homeowners can do this themselves; we do it free as part of any other countertop service visit.</li>
      <li><strong>"Child lock" lockout:</strong> Not a repair — most calls about a Genius Prestige that "won't respond to the keypad" are the child-lock feature engaged accidentally. We walk you through the unlock sequence on the phone at no charge before scheduling a visit.</li>
      <li><strong>Bulb replacement:</strong> $8-$15 part, 15-minute swap. Cosmetic but customer-noticed; worth doing alongside any other service.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Panasonic jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Four representative Panasonic service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see on Panasonic across each environment.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>NN-SN966S Inverter built-in, Beverly Hills condo</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Owner reported the unit "humming but not heating" — fan and turntable running, food coming out cold after 4-minute cycles. Approximately 7 years old per the install paperwork.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> RF detector confirmed no microwave output. Bias-current meter on the magnetron read open. High-voltage diode tested clean.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> OEM Panasonic magnetron replacement (in stock on the truck). Verified RF output post-repair on a water-load test cycle. Total time on-site: 65 minutes.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> $315 total.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>NN-CS894S combo steam oven, Bel Air estate</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Steam cycle "weak" per the homeowner; pre-heating, but the steam phase wasn't producing visible vapor and bread proofs were running flat. Unit was 6 years old.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Steam reservoir inspection showed heavy limescale buildup at the heater element and outlet. Door seal also showed thermal-cycle degradation at the upper corners.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Citric-solution descale flush and full reservoir clean, OEM door seal replacement, calibration cycle on the steam generator. Verified normal steam output post-service.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $385 total. 95 minutes on-site, completed same-day.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Genius Prestige countertop, Brentwood apartment</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> "Won't start" — keypad lit, display normal, but pressing Start did nothing. Property manager call for a tenant unit.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Triple-interlock door-switch system: middle switch reading open. Door alignment had drifted approximately 2 mm at the upper hinge — a common pre-2015 Genius Prestige pattern.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Door-switch replacement plus alignment shim at upper hinge. Tested through full Start cycle with door open and closed.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $95 total. 35 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>NN-SD681S countertop, Westwood condo</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Turntable not rotating; food cooking unevenly. Interior bulb also out. Unit was about 5 years old.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Drive coupler cracked at the spindle interface — a known Panasonic countertop wear item. Bulb cosmetic, separate.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> OEM coupler replacement, bulb replacement done in the same visit. Test cycle confirmed normal turntable rotation and full interior lighting.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $65 total. 25 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 LA CONTEXT + REPAIR vs REPLACE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06, Where we see Panasonic in LA</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Panasonic microwaves across Greater Los Angeles.</h2>

    <p>Panasonic's installed base across our service area clusters in three patterns. <strong>NN-CS combo steam ovens</strong> live in estate kitchens — Bel Air, Beverly Hills, Hollywood Hills, Pacific Palisades — almost always as a second oven, not the primary. <strong>NN-SN Inverter built-ins</strong> show up across high-end Westside condos (West Hollywood, Brentwood, Westwood) where developers spec them into trim-kit cabinetry as part of integrated kitchen packages — and we'll often see batches of NN-SN units in a single building all reach magnetron end-of-life within a six-month window because they were installed together. <strong>Genius Prestige countertops</strong> are spread across the broader rental and condo market, often replaced by property management on a 4-6 year cycle.</p>

    <p>Hard-water scaling on NN-CS combo units is concentrated in the Hills neighborhoods — Bel Air sees it fastest, Beverly Hills and Hollywood Hills close behind. Coastal humidity (Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Manhattan Beach) doesn't materially affect microwave service life, but it can accelerate door-seal degradation on combo steam units by a year or two compared to inland installations.</p>

    <p>The honest repair-versus-replace math: built-in NN-SN units almost always favor repair under 8 years (cabinet rework cost dominates). NN-CS combo steam ovens favor repair well past 10 years (the replacement runs $3,000+). Countertop Genius Prestige units are case-by-case — a $90 door-switch repair on a 4-year-old unit is fine, a $300 magnetron on a 7-year-old countertop usually loses to a $200 replacement. We'll tell you the math before you authorize anything.</p>
  </div>
</section>

